Cryptography:

Asymmetric, a method that uses a pair of mathematically linked keys (public and private) where one encrypts and the other decrypts.

Symmetric, method that uses the same secret key for both encryption and decryption

Block Ciphers, a symmetric encryption algorithm that processes fixed size blocks of data (e.g. 128 bits) at a time using a shared key.

Hashing, a one way function that transforms data of any size into a fixed length string (hash) that cannot be feasibly reversed

SHA, Securing Hashing Algorithm, a family of cryptographic hash functions (like SHA-256) designed to produce unique, fixed length digests for secure data integrity verification.

MD, Message Digest, a family of cryptographic hash functions like (md5) that produce a fixed length digest of input data, mainly used for integrity checks but now considered weak against modern attacks.



















